The dataset contains the following columns:

  • DateTime: Date and time of the record
  • BHhkwOnOff: 1 if the CHP unit was powered on, 0 otherwise
  • AussenTemperatur: Outdoor temperature in °C
  • SpeicherUnten, SpeicherMitte, SpeicherOben: The storage temperatures in °C at the bottom, mid, and the top.

Problem description

Around the 11th of January a software update was performed. That update lead to a malfunction of the control of the CHP unit in the following days. Between the beginning of January and the 11th the CHP unit was working normally. That data will serve as our training data for a semi-supervised anomaly detection and a unsupervised anomaly detection. The anomaly detection should be based on the storage temperatures (last three features).

# store the features that will be used for the anomaly detection
features <- c("SpeicherUnten", "SpeicherMitte", "SpeicherOben")
# select the data from 1.1 - 11.1
trainIndex <- 1:15000
train <- dat[trainIndex,]

1.1 One-class SVM Anomaly Detection

Train a one-class SVM model using the e1071 package. The SVM predicts if a data point belongs to the normal class (output is true) or not (output is false).

Tune the nu parameter in order to get a reasonable classifications on the training set.

library(e1071) # contains svm model
# train a svm

svm.model <- svm(train[,features], type = "one-classification", nu = 0.01)

# determine which points are considered normal on the training set
pred_train <- predict(svm.model, train[,features])

Count the number of normal and anomalous instances.

table(pred_train)
## pred_train
## FALSE  TRUE 
##   149 14851

Plot the training data, color the points as grey (normal) or red (anomaly)

plot(dat$DateTime[trainIndex], dat$SpeicherUnten[trainIndex], 
     xlab = "Date Time", ylab = "Speicher Unten (Celsius Degrees)", 
     col = ifelse(pred_train, "azure4", "red"))

plot(dat$DateTime[trainIndex], dat$SpeicherMitte[trainIndex], 
     xlab = "Date Time", ylab = "Speicher Mitte (Celsius Degrees)",
     col = ifelse(pred_train, "azure3", "red"))

plot(dat$DateTime[trainIndex], dat$SpeicherOben[trainIndex],
      xlab = "Date Time", ylab = "Speicher Oben (Celsius Degrees)",
     col = ifelse(pred_train, "azure2", "red"))

pairs(cbind(1:15000, train[,4:6]), 
      col = ifelse(pred_train, "azure3", "red"))

How does the parameter nu influence the one-class classification boundary?

Your answer: The higher the nu, the higher the anomaly values the svm model classifies. This value was tested at 0.5, 0.1, 0.01. Finally, 0.01 was found as the best value. nu is a percentage taken by the model as anomaly values. For the training dataset, the number of anomaly instances is 149

Use the one-class SVM to find anomalies in the entire data set

# determine which points are considered normal on the whole data set

1.2 Unsupervized Anomaly Detection: Isolation Forest

Get an idea how the isolation Forest (iForest) works on wikipedia or orginal doc. In contrast to the one-cass svm the iForest creates an anomaly score for each data instance.

# load package containing isolation forests
library(isotree)
## Warning: package 'isotree' was built under R version 4.0.4
# train a isoForest with 10 trees
isoForest <- isolation.forest(train[,features], ntrees = 100)

Use the iForest to compute an anomaly score for the training data instances.

anomalyScore <- predict(isoForest, train[,features])
threshold <- 0.62

Plot the anomaly score for the training set.

plot(train$DateTime, anomalyScore, 
      xlab = "Date Time", ylab = "Anomaly Score",
     col = ifelse(anomalyScore > threshold, "red", "azure3"))

Does the training set contain anomalies? Can you explain them?

Your Answer: Yes, the training data has some anomalies which are shown on red color. Most of these anomalies correspond to the values shown as outliers in the SpeicherMitte Data

Decide what a reasonable anomaly score threshold could be for the training data. Count the anomalies in the training set based using that threshold.

The threshold selected was 0.62. This value was found after testing different values and finding the best match for the outliers (red color dots) shown on the plot 

isanomaly = anomalyScore > threshold

Briefly discuss and interpret the results and the choice of the threshhold.

Your answer:

The threshold was selected so that the number of anomalies observed in the plots are not very high and not very low. If the number of anomalies is very high, datavalues that are in the normal range can be taken as anomalies. If the number of anomalies is very low, then incorrect values could be taken. For the reasons explained before, plotting the variables with the threshold is very immportant so that the correct threshold can be selected.

1.3 Your model

Repeat the previous procedure for an anomaly detection method of your choice. Document your results and briefly discuss and compare them to the two previous approaches.

The method chosen is Multivariate Outlier Detection and Replacement by Random Forest Predictions. However, the replacement method was not carried out.

library(outForest)
## Warning: package 'outForest' was built under R version 4.0.4
out <- outForest(train[,features], threshold = 5, replace = "no", allow_predictions = TRUE, min.node.size=10 )

Your answer: Multivariate Outlier Detection and Replacement by Random Forest Predictions

This method does not process the data by instances but by variables. For this reason, despite the fact that the number of instances of the train data is 15000, the number of processed values was 45000, of which 106 were classified as anomalous. This is a very low value if compared with those classified by the two previous methods.

plot(dat$DateTime[trainIndex], dat$SpeicherUnten[trainIndex],
     xlab = "Date Time", ylab = "Speicher Unten (Celsius Degrees)", 
     col = ifelse(SU_outlier, "red", "azure4") )

     col = ifelse(SM_outlier, "red", "azure3") )

plot(dat$DateTime[trainIndex], dat$SpeicherOben[trainIndex],
     xlab = "Date Time", ylab = "Speicher Oben (Celsius Degrees)", 
     col = ifelse(SO_outlier, "red", "azure2") )

For this dataset, this method is not appropriate. Let’s see why: The method classifies properly the anomalies in the SpeicherMitte variable However, it does not detect them well for the variable SpeicherOben

Each numeric variable to be checked for outliers is regressed onto all other variables using a random forest. If the scaled absolute difference between observed value and out-of-bag prediction is larger than some predefined threshold (default is 3, for this case was 5 ), then a value is considered an outlier

plot(out)

plot(out, what = "scores")
